<TEXT>
the reagan administration would find nothing 
embarrassing in concluding a meeting with soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev that produced no breakthroughs or agreements a white 
house spokesman said monday 
but the two sides expanding the superpower dialogue decided to 
set up a separate session between secretary of state george p 
shultz and soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze 
the session will be held at the us mission to the united 
nations on wednesday morning in advance of gorbachevs luncheon on 
governors island ny with president reagan and presidentelect 
george bush state department spokesman charles e redman said 
while striving to limit american expectations for the luncheon 
meeting white house spokesman marlin fitzwater acknowledged that 
gorbachev could spring a surprise there 
reminded that various soviet officials and analysts have said 
over the weekend that gorbachev had more in mind than just a cordial 
talk with reagan and bush fitzwater said im sure the soviets 
want to put a positive face on this trip 
the us embassy in moscow citing comments of a soviet foreign 
trade official has advised washington in a cablegram to expect 
several new proposals aimed at lowering us limits on trade and 
lending with communist countries the new york times reported in 
tuesday editions 
the proposals are said to include soviet access to american stock 
and financial markets clearing the way for the soviet union to 
issue bonds and other securities in the united states 
gorbachev may also use the trip to express soviet interest in 
gaining access to several international economic organizations 
including the world bank the cable said according to the times 
the soviet leader also may discuss advance arrangements for an 
early summit with bush and plans to use his un speech to call for 
new momentum in dealing with a variety of international issues 
soviet academician georgi arbatov told a new york news conference 
monday 
another soviet official central committee spokesman nikolai 
shishlin offered a similar assessment saying the key issue of 
gorbachevs visit will be discussing ways to translate his new 
political thinking into progress in international relations 
but fitzwater said he was unaware of any major new soviet 
initiative and suggested that us officials would not let 
gorbachev put them under pressure to respond immediately to new 
proposals 
we are being very realistic fitzwater said explaining the 
us situation this way 
we have a president who is leaving office in a few weeks who 
is not going to be making any promises that he is not here to keep 
and we have a new president who will be taking office in a few 
weeks who is not going to be making commitments when he doesnt 
have an administration in power that can fully analyze and make 
these judgments 
so we find nothing embarrassing or in any way negative about 
characterizing this meeting as a friendly discussion fitzwater 
said an open airing of issues between us and a healthy approach 
towards continuity 
he said the fact that us and soviet officials can sit down and 
talk without there having to be tangible immediate results or 
agreements illustrates the strength of the new relationship 
between washington and moscow 
this meeting is symbolic of that the fact that you can have 
meetings without having 10month kinds of summits summits about 10 
months apart that weve known in the past he said 
reagan and gorbachev had a fiveday summit in moscow last spring 
the two exchanged the final instruments of ratification for the 
treaty banning shortand intermediaterange nuclear weapons during 
that meeting 
but there is no reason to expect anything more than that from 
the us side at this juncture he added the spokesman said for 
instance that at the present time there is no call for a meeting 
in new york of the ussoviet arms negotiating teams 
fitzwater also said that neither he nor other us officials know 
what gorbachev plans to tell the un general assembly in his 
address wednesday which is scheduled just before the kremlin leader 
travels to governors island to meet reagan and bush 
he said that the language of the soviet advance team over the 
weekend was optimistic and upbeat and so forth but it was all 
very general 
its certainly true that we dont expect to be making any new 
proposals and we dont expect any in the sense of requiring 
onthesite response or any onlocation negotiating or anything like 
that fitzwater said obviously theyll have new ideas or 
things to say may have fresh approaches to some of the regional 
problems and thats all well and good 
if a surprise proposal is advanced by gorbachev he said well 
say thank you and well take a look at them 
fitzwater said that reagan briefed on the eastwest situation by 
national security adviser colin d powell and bush joined the 
president for mondays session in the oval office 
</TEXT>
