<TEXT>
a 16 million damage award won by a man who said 
he got aids from a bloodbased medicine he took for hemophilia was 
reversed monday by a federal judge who ruled the evidence did not 
support a jurys verdict 
us district judge orinda evans said in a 14page ruling that 
the verdict reached by a federal jury after two days of 
deliberation in october had no basis in law or fact she reversed 
the verdict in favor of randy l jones 35 and granted judgment for 
miles laboratories 
miles based in elkhart ind manufactures koate a bloodbased 
factor viii clotting product which jones took to control a mild 
case of hemophilia after surgery at clayton general hospital in 1983 
jones who lives in the atlanta area was diagnosed in 1985 as 
infected with the virus that causes aids two years later he was 
told by doctors he had developed the disease itself 
in his lawsuit jones contended the drug he took had been 
contaminated with the aids virus contracted by an unemployed texas 
man who allegedly sold plasma 40 times to a plasma center in austin 
texas which in turn supplied miles 
the texas man died of aids less than six weeks after his last 
plasma sale in september 1983 the suit said 
jones contended in his suit that more than 60000 vials of koate 
were contaminated with the aids virus because of the texas mans 
infection he charged that miles was negligent in acquiring and 
using the infected plasma 
miles in its appeal denied any negligence 
bud modersbach the berkeley calif counsel for cutter 
biologicals the miles division which manufactures koate said 
monday that the jurys decision was overruled because it was so 
clearcut 
modersbach said the company had initiated a highrisk donor 
screening program in february 1983 months before jones took the 
drug and he said much less was known then about aids transmission 
than is now known 
he said the jury may have acted more on emotion than on the facts 
in the trial 
judge evans said in her ruling that jones did not address miles 
argument that he could just as well have gotten aids from other 
blood factor products 
george h connell jr jones attorney said he planned to appeal 
