professor raymond levy in whose tests martin participated 
cautioned that the drug treats the symptoms not the disease and is 
unlikely to be a cure in any sense 
martin was one of the first volunteers when tests of the drug 
tetrahydroaminoacridine or tha began at londons institute of 
psychiatry in march and his condition improved immediately his 
wife judith said monday 
he responded not miraculously but there was certainly a 
reduction in the deterioration which was immediately noticeable 
she told british broadcasting corp radio from the couples 
cambridge home 
he didnt have attacks or irritability nearly so often it 
certainly appeared encouraging from fairly early on 
alzheimers disease is a progressive irreversible neurological 
disease with no known cause or cure victims mostly elderly people 
suffer gradual memory loss disorientation and personality changes 
levy who is conducting the trials told the associated press 
that tha is not a cure 
it doesnt reverse the process and i think its unlikely to be 
a cure in any sense he said its dealing with symptoms 
really rather than the basic cause of the disease 
levy a professor of oldage psychiatry said tha seems to 
preserve a chemical messenger called acetylcholine that helps 
control memory 
however brain cells die as alzheimers disease progresses and a 
drug such as tha can work only as long as there are enough living 
cells to produce sufficient levels of acetylcholine 
martin a biochemist won the nobel prize in 1952 for his work on 
chromatography a method of separating chemical substances his 
discoveries transformed chemistry and are still widely used in 
medicine and industry 
mrs martin said her husband began losing his memory four years 
ago and could not work because he forgot everything he read 
tha has sideeffects including a risk of liver damage but mrs 
martin said as a scientist and as a scientists wife we are both 
wellequipped to observe anything that might be going wrong 
other side effects reported from tha experiments include nausea 
vomiting and allergic reactions 
the drug hit the headlines in 1986 with a report of effectiveness 
by a california investigator but this year the us food and drug 
