nations secondlargest city says to a scientist who recommends 
that building codes be reevaluated 
the elysian park fault unknown until it caused the deadly oct 
1 1987 whittier narrows earthquake is about 10 miles wide and 60 
miles long 
it runs from santa monica bay east through beverly hills 
downtown los angeles and monterey park then southeast to suburban 
whittier fullerton yorba linda and corona said geophysicist egill 
hauksson 
while mapping the extent of that fault university of southern 
california scientists also discovered the 40by10mile 
torrancewilmington fault stretching from santa monica bay southeast 
through oil fields in torrance and los angeles wilmington district 
the palos verdes peninsula long beach and offshore from newport 
beach 
haukssons study of the faults known as thrust faults hidden by 
giant folds in earths crust was scheduled to be presented today at 
the american geophysical unions fall meeting in san francisco 
theres growing evidence that theres a fairly extensive system 
of those types of faults in the los angeles basin said tom 
heaton scientist in charge of the pasadena office of the us 
geological survey which financed haukssons study 
thrust faults have caused damaging and sometimes very large 
earthquakes in other parts of the world heaton said 
hauksson said his study suggests the five segments of the elysian 
park fault break in separate earthquakes so the largest jolts 
possible likely would measure 66 on the richter scale on a 15mile 
segment that runs under downtown los angeles and 68 on the segment 
that runs from yorba linda northwest toward whittier he added 
but hauksson said researchers cant rule out the possibility the 
entire fault could snap at once in a major 75magnitude jolt that 
would cause worse damage in los angeles than the longfeared 
8magnitude big one on the more distant san andreas fault 
it took only a fourmile segment of the elysian park fault to 
trigger the magnitude 59 whittier quake which with its 53 
aftershock killed eight people injured about 200 and caused 358 
million in damage 
the torrancewilmington fault could produce a quake with a 
magnitude between 66 and 68 or so hauksson said 
seismologists still lack enough information to determine how 
frequently moderate and large quakes occur on the elysian park and 
torrancewilmington faults he added 
he said the faults pose such a shaking hazard that building codes 
should be reevaluated 
downtown skyscrapers would suffer broken windows but survive a 
66magnitude quake which would knock down a lot of old brick 
buildings hauksson said 
the faults are about 10 miles wide because thrust faults are like 
giant subterranean ramps in which ground on one side of the fault 
moves upward at an angle over ground on the other side 
for years scientists mainly feared strikeslip faults such as 
the san andreas where ground on one side jerks horizontally past 
ground on the other side such a fault triggered saturdays 50 jolt 
that left 32 people with minor injuries 
but hauksson and heaton said concealed thrust faults may pose a 
greater danger than strikeslip faults 
hauksson mapped the elysian park fault and discovered the 
torrancewilmington fault by analyzing 200 quakes mostly magnitude 
25 to 40 that shook metropolitan los angeles from 1977 to 1988 
he found 40 percent of the quakes were centered on the two faults 
a 1980 government study said the big one a magnitude 8 
great quake on the san andreas some 60 miles from downtown los 
angeles could kill up to 14000 people seriously injure 55000 
and cause 17 billion in damage 
a 1981 federal study said a magnitude 75 quake on the newport 
inglewood fault the major strikeslip fault inside los angeles 
could kill up to 21000 people hospitalize 84000 and leave 630000 
with less serious injuries 
before we knew about the thrust faults we knew the newport 
inglewood was there hauksson said now weve discovered two 
fault structures both of which are somewhat bigger than the 
newportinglewood that tells you the earthquake potential has gone 
up 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

