<TEXT>
in trying to break the palestinian uprising 
israel is imposing collective economic punishments ranging from 
sealing up village shops to blocking farmers from tilling their 
fields a human rights group alleges 
the arab group says in a report released monday that the 
sanctions are also aimed at furthering the longterm israeli goal of 
colonizing the occupied west bank and gaza strip 
the scope of the uprising gave the authorities an excuse to 
use such sanctions on a much wider indeed unprecedented scale 
says the report by law in the service of man also known as al haq 
such punishments have almost always been of a collective nature 
al haq founded by palestinian lawyers is affiliated with the 
genevabased international commission of jurists 
its report came three days before the first anniversary of the 
uprising against israeli occupation of the west bank and gaza strip 
more than 300 palestinians and 11 israelis have died in the violence 
al haq charges that israels sanctions are aimed at maintaining 
the occupied lands as israels secondlargest export market after 
the united states and at making any opposition to occupation 
policies prohibitively expensive 
a spokesman for the israeli military government in the occupied 
territories who spoke on condition that his name not be used 
denied that israel uses economic sanctions to punish palestinians 
collectively 
we try very hard to diffentiate between the great number of 
people trying to get away from violence and the minority causing 
trouble he said 
he said israel imposes sanctions only to prevent violence or to 
force people to pay back taxes he acknowledged however that 
curfews imposed for security reasons have prevented farmers from 
working their fields 
al haq in its report says one of the most harmful sanctions is 
a limit imposed on the amount of money palestinians can bring into 
the occupied territories and israel authorities say the move is 
intended to block money from getting to palestine liberation 
organization activists 
but alhaq noted that the blanket limit on the money palestinians 
can bring in from jordan to 200 dinars or about 600 disrupts 
businesses and institutions that keep their assets in dinars the 
jordanian currency is legal tender in the west bank 
a limitation of about 1200 each on money brought from elsewhere 
has hurt families dependent on remittances from workers overseas 
the report says 
it also notes that to stop palestinian general strikes a main 
tactic of the uprising the army has broken open closed stores at 
times it has welded shut doors of shops to prevent them from opening 
when the strikes are over 
farmers have suffered the most from sanctions imposed by the 
israelis the report says adding if a farmer is not permitted 
access to his fields in order to irrigate the crop spray it or 
harvest it the entire crop may be lost 
in the village of qalqiliya it says many crops were lost when a 
25day curfew in march and april prevented farmers from getting to 
their fields 
in several cases the report says israeli authorities prevented 
the marketing of olive oil a major moneymaker for palestinians by 
closing down olive presses and confiscating the keys israeli 
authorites say such moves are aimed at forcing tax evaders to pay up 
al haq noted that israels efforts to break a tax boycott also a 
tactic of the uprising included disrupting peoples lives by 
refusing to issue necessary papers such as business licenses and 
marriage and birth certificates unless all back taxes are paid 
the group also accused israeli authorities of seeking to undercut 
palestinian society by closing down labor union offices charities 
and other institutions israel has accused such groups of being 
fronts for antiisraeli activity 
among institutions closed are 24 west bank union offices a 
federation of charities in israeliannexed arab east jerusalem and 
the organization for the care of ecology in qalqaliya 
the sweeping nature of the measures against popular 
organizations seems to indicate an intent to undermine the 
institutional infrastructure of the palestinian population the al 
haq report says 
