<TEXT>
richard m daley steps into this citys mayoral 
race as the apparent frontrunner but gaining the office his father 
held for 21 years may be difficult 
daley cook countys top prosecutor formally announced monday he 
would seek the office that richard j daley held from 1955 until his 
death in office in 1976 but opponents said the daley dominance is a 
thing of the past 
the mayors office is not an heirloom to be passed on from one 
generation to the next acting mayor eugene sawyer said 
however an october gallup poll showed the 46yearold daley who 
last month overwhelmingly won a third term as states attorney with 
a commanding 15point lead over alderman tim evans his closest 
pursuer in a crowded field 
sawyer whos expected to announce his candidacy within a week 
was 12 points behind evans and had support of just 10 percent of 
those polled 
daley rejected criticism that his successful bid would mean a 
return to the machinestyle politics practiced by his father who 
used patronage jobs to maintain a political army and keep control of 
the mayors office the elder daley exerted such influence in local 
and national democratic circles that he was called boss and 
kingmaker 
first of all my father died in 1976 they critics should get 
on with it daley said at a news conference 
im proud of my name daley said my father was a great 
mayor and a great father but all the candidates have to run on 
their record and ive got a record both as a states attorney and 
a state senator 
daley is the seventh candidate to enter the democratic primary 
and the fourth white in a city that made harold washington its first 
black mayor in 1983 and has split its vote along racial lines since 
while the daley name lent immediate credibility to his bid the 
lessons he learned in a 1983 mayoral try may prove more significant 
in that years democratic primary daley split the white vote 
with thenmayor jane byrne coming in third and catapulting 
washington into the mayors chair 
but in an almost complete reversal of events washingtons death 
last november has fractured the black voting bloc that was so 
unified behind the former congressman and neither evans nor sawyer 
who are black appear willing to step aside 
daley however rejected notions that he could win simply by 
appealing to whites who make up about half the citys population 
im not interested in running as the white candidate or 
serving as mayor for half the people said daley 
fighting crime is not a white issue or a black issue schools 
is not a white or black issue protecting taxpayers is not a white 
or black issue 
the democratic primary is scheduled for feb 28 the special 
election set last month by the illinois supreme court to complete 
washingtons second term follows on april 4 
evans had no immediate reaction said his press secretary 
sharon jenkinsbrown but another democratic challenger alderman 
danny davis predicted a voter backlash because of daleys 
willingness to leave his states attorney post so soon after his 
reelection 
the other democratic candidates are aldermen edward burke and 
lawrence bloom former chicago park district superintendent edmund 
kelly and former state sen james taylor 
city gop leaders were still looking for a candidate though at 
least one republican edward howlett has announce plans to run for 
the partys nomination 
