<TEXT>
soviet officials and afghan guerrilla 
leaders said in statements released today that they will meet in 
pakistan for more facetoface talks following two days of 
unprecedented meetings in saudi arabia 
the saudi press agency released statements from both delegation 
leaders soviet deputy foreign minister yuli vorontsov and afghan 
guerrilla leader burhanuddin rabbani saying the talks would resume 
shortly in pakistan 
no date was given 
pakistan is one of the main supporters of the guerrillas seven 
guerrilla groups form a loose alliance headed by rabbani that is 
based in peshawar pakistan a city near the afghan border 
the news agency said the soviets renewed a pledge to adhere to a 
un accord and withdraw their troops from afghanistan by feb 15 
and possibly earlier it said vorontsov made the promise during a 
meeting with king fahd of saudi arabia 
the delegates issued their statements late monday their talks 
were held saturday and sunday in the mountain resort of taif 
the statements indicated that the talks focused on the issue of 
an interim government in afghanistan and that both sides needed time 
for consultations before talks resume rabbani also stressed a 
demand for war reparations 
moslem guerrillas have been at war with afghanistans 
sovietbacked government for nine years soviet troops intervened in 
december 1979 and began withdrawing in may after the signing of the 
geneva accord 
the guerrillas did not sign the accord and the soviets have 
suspended their troop withdrawal because of guerrilla attacks 
reporting on the meeting with king fahd the press agency said 
vorontsov affirmedwhat was previously declared by the the 
soviet presidentof the determination of the soviet union to pull 
out its forces from afghanistan at the defined time and perhaps 
before that 
rabbani said he and his delegation entered the talks on the basis 
of the principles that afghanistan was and would remain an 
independent free islamic state and that the soviet withdrawal was 
mandatory the news agency said 
vorontsov said he came to taif to fulfill moscows will to give 
new momentum to the settlement adding we believe the meetings 
were useful and will contribute to ending the war and the 
formation of an afghani government on a wide basis 
