<TEXT>
an anonymous phone call led police to a california 
scientist who fled 18 months ago while awaiting trial on fraud 
charges stemming from his job at a nuclear weapons research 
facility officials said 
police lt john summers of suburban chandler said ronald k 
stump 49 was arrested without incident monday in his motor home 
he was sought by the fbi on a warrant charging him with unlawful 
flight to avoid prosecution 
summers said stump apparently had been living in the motor home 
which was parked behind a service station 
stump worked at lawrence livermore national laboratory in 
livermore calif for more than 25 years when he disappeared in 
april 1987 the department of energy facility 40 miles east of san 
francisco designs us nuclear weapons 
but fbi agent chuck latting in san franciso said said the fbis 
interest in the scientist stemmed less from his topsecurity rating 
and nuclear research than his flight from trial 
he was just able to get some bucks and he flew the coop 
latting said people around here got real exercised wondering how 
come we didnt put every agent in the world out to find him and we 
knew that if we went through a normal fugitive investigation that we 
would get him and thats what we did 
stump was charged with fraud for his alleged role in the 
laboratorys 1983 purchase of a 250000 machine that didnt work 
assistant us attorney rodolfo orjales in california said 
earlier this year that stump may have worked out a kickback deal 
with a partner of the company that sold the equipment to the 
laboratory 
stump who filed for bankruptcy in 1980 owed 10000 to the 
partner 
officials said stump had access to the laboratorys topsecret 
tritium facility and other national clearances but latting said 
stump never was considered a national security risk even though he 
left the country tritium is a radioactive form of hydrogen used in 
some forms of nuclear bombs 
apparently he was not handling any military classified material 
or doing any classifiedtype work although he was technically very 
qualified latting said 
allegations that federal authorities failed to investigate 
stumps disappearance and other employee violations at livermore and 
other laboratories have prompted an investigation by a house 
subcommittee 
livermore administrators were worried about protecting the labs 
public image and chose to let stump go free rather than risk 
unfavorable publicity according to investigators on the labs 
security force and in congress 
