<TEXT>
when soviet president mikhail s gorbachev has 
lunch in new york on wednesday with the outgoing and incoming 
american presidents afghanistan is likely to be the most divisive 
issue they discuss 
a possible soviet refusal to fulfill its commitment to withdraw 
its troops from afghanistan by a feb 15 deadline could present to 
george bush his first foreign policy challenge he will be sworn in 
just 26 days before that date 
any such move by the soviets clearly would get bushs relations 
with the kremlin off on the wrong foot 
the luncheon will take place amid official predictions that both 
president reagan and bush will encourage gorbachev to meet the 
deadline 
i think theyve made the decision to get out of afghanistan 
vernon walters us ambassador to the united nations said on 
cbstvs this morning program today i think theyre going to 
stick with it 
bush however has said he has no intention of trying to upstage 
the boss it will be president reagans meeting bush has said 
since the geneva accords which spell out terms of the soviet 
withdrawal were signed last april moscow and washington have been 
accusing each other of violations 
the soviets maintain that us and pakistani support for the 
afghan rebels has been excessive while the reagan administration 
insists the soviets are guilty of a similar infraction with their 
backing for the communist regime in kabul 
adding to the drama about whether the soviets will comply was an 
announcement by moscow in early november that it was suspending the 
removal of troops 
this did not constitute a violation since the agreement sets only 
two deadlines moscow complied with a promise to have half of its 
more than 100000 troops back home by aug 15 the next deadline is 
feb 15 but the pace of the second phase of the withdrawal is up to 
the soviets 
thus far the conventional wisdom is that the soviets will meet 
the deadline while doing everything it can in the interim to bolster 
the kabul regimes military and political position 
most analysts believe that gorbachev long ago made a political 
decision to withdraw from afghanistan to reverse that course now 
would expose gorbachev to international indignation and would mean 
continued soviet military involvement in a war which soviets 
apparently have concluded was both costly and unwinnable 
still the soviets seem genuinely anguished by the level of 
american and pakistani backing for the mujahedeen rebels 
in september soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze said 
as soon as the soviet troops began to withdraw a nonstop 
production line of violations was set in motion 
other soviet foreign ministry officials have raised the 
possibility the feb 15 deadline might be ignored to guard against 
that outcome the state department has been urging the rebels to 
exercise restraint toward soviet troops 
the reagan administration has promised continued support to the 
mujahedeen rebels so long as moscow continues its backing for the 
afghan government 
bush has indicated he plans to continue the reagan policy a 
point he made two days after his election when he met with the 
leader of the afghan rebel alliance burhanuddin rabbani 
