<TEXT>
the supreme court today saved the coal mining 
industry from paying potentially billions of dollars in additional 
benefits to miners with black lung disease 
but at the same time the justices ruled that more than 8000 
miners with pending black lung claims may be eligible to receive 
hundreds of millions of dollars in benefits 
by a 54 vote the court said that miners with less than 10 years 
of work in the mines are eligible to claim benefits if there is 
other evidence they are disabled that class of workers is estimated 
by the government to be around 8000 to 10000 miners 
but the court also overturned a lower court ruling that could 
have opened the way for claims by possibly more than 100000 miners 
seeking as much as 136 billion in benefits 
the larger group is barred from receiving benefits because miners 
in that class failed to pursue adminisrative remedies or to appeal 
to the courts within the prescribed time the justices ruled 
justice antonin scalia writing for the court said congress 
never intended to exclude from benefit eligibility miners who worked 
less than 10 years 
we do not sit to determine what congress ought to have done 
given the evidence before it but to apply what congress enacted 
and the exclusion of shortterm miners from the benefitsfinds 
no support in the statute scalia said 
on the other hand he continued nothing in federal law requires 
the government to reopen settled claims 
there is not even a colorable basis for the contention that 
congress has imposed a duty to reconsider finally determined 
claims he said 
he was joined by justices william j brennan thurgood marshall 
harry a blackmun and anthony m kennedy 
the four dissenters agreed that settled cases should not be 
reopened but they also said that miners with less than 10 years of 
work are not entitled to the benefits 
justice john paul stevens wrote the dissenting opinion joined by 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices byron r white and 
sandra day oconnor 
the ruling is at least an important partial victory for the 
reagan administration as well as the coal mining industry 
the administration challenged a ruling by the 8th us circuit 
court of appeals that justice department lawyers said could force 
tremendous additional cost on the overburdened fund that pays black 
lung benefits 
the 8th circuit court in the ruling overturned today said the 
department of labor must take a fresh look at claims that were 
denied in the late 1970s and early 1980s the appeals court had 
directed the department to use liberalized standards adopted by 
congress in 1977 to determine eligibility for benefits 
congress had previously created a special fund to pay off claims 
by miners with black lung disease also known as pneumoconiosis 
coal mine operators already owe the government some 3 billion 
that has been loaned to the fund from the federal treasury 
in other action the court 
dismissed the appeal of an unwed california father seeking to 
restore a parental relationship with his 7yearold daughter 
eight days after hearing arguments in edward mcnamaras case the 
court dismissed the appeal for want of a properly presented 
federal question 
there was no recorded dissent 
the justices had been expected to use his case to decide whether 
unwed fathers who actively seek custody of their children may be 
stripped of all parental rights if adoption is deemed in the 
childrens best interest 
ruled unanimously that federal employees holding sensitive 
spyagency jobs are not entitled to administrative hearings when 
fired as security risks 
the justices reversed a lower courts ruling that would have 
required such a hearing for a national security agency employee who 
says he was fired because of his homosexual activities 
the black lung cases are pittston coal group vs sebben 87821 
whitfield vs sebben 87827 and office of workers compensation 
vs broyles 871095 
</TEXT>
