the national transportation safety board has 
published its final report on the crash of continental flight 1713 
reaffirming the boards opinion that human error caused the accident 
during takeoff in a snowstorm 
the report reaffirmed the ntsb investigators opinion that the 
crash which killed 28 of the planes 82 passengers and crew 
members including the captain and first officer was caused by the 
captains failure to deice the aircraft after a takeoff delay in 
steady snowfall 
it reiterated their opinion that confusion between the flight 
crew and air traffic controllers contributed to the accident by 
helping to delay the takeoff 
the report issued monday also restated the investigators 
belief that another contributing factor was the absence of 
regulatory or management controls which led to the pairing of the continental 
dc9 bound for boise idaho crashed on takeoff 
nov 15 1987 at stapleton international airport 
the 90page report puts in written form what the board discussed 
on sept 27 during its probablecause hearing on the crash 
the formal report reaffirms earlier findings that the accident 
resulted from a combination of errors by inexperienced pilots frank 
zvonek 43 and lee bruecher 26 and the weather 
bruecher who was at the controls was faulted for lifting the 
nose too soon and causing the plane to stall he had completed just 
36 hours of flight time including simulator practice on the dc9 
and had not flown at all in the 24 days prior to the crash 
zvonek was an experienced boeing 737 copilot but had only 
limited dc9 flight time he was faulted for failing to return the 
plane for a second spray of deicing fluid even though it sat on the 
ground in snow and freezing temperatures for 27 minutes before 
takeoff 
