<TEXT>
the 360yearold royal warship wasa 
moved to its final berth tuesday with hundreds of people gathering 
in gray and snowy weather to cheer its last voyage 
designed as the mightiest ship of its day the wasa sank on its 
maiden voyage in 1628 it was salvaged from stockholm bay in 1961 
and displayed in a temporary museum winning acclaim as one of the 
best preserved ships of its kind 
it was placed on a pontoon and encased in an aluminum shield to 
protect it during the 275yard voyage to the site of a new museum 
under construction 
a 24pound cannon retrieved from the wasa roared the announcement 
of the ships arrival at its final port of call 
i have dreamt of this moment and gone through it so many times 
in my mind that it feels like a deja vu experience said anders 
franzen who rediscovered the ship and supervised its salvage 
the new museum which will open in june 1990 is a huge 28 
million coppercolored enclosure facing the royal palace on the 
stockholm waterfront 
the move ends years of discussions on the fate of the ship which 
was to be the flagship of a swedish empire stretching from the 
scandinavian peninsula across the baltic and into russia 
topheavy with armaments the wasa caught a mighty gust of wind 
and capsized only minutes after being launched 
crowds lined the shore to see if it would topple once more 
it has been a constant nightmare that history will repeat 
itself said franzen a retired scientist 
transporting the ship into the new dock became a test of 
precision for the tug towing the 22yardhigh encasement he said 
the wasa adorned with most of its original 700 goldleaf 
sculptures has become a symbol of ancient sweden at the height of 
its power it attracts 500000 tourists a year 
</TEXT>
