<TEXT>
people should not take comfort in this years 
apparently improved ozone levels over antarctica a climate expert 
warned tuesday 
this year there is a substantial recovery in antarctic ozone 
levels dr robert watson of the national aeronautics and space 
administration told the opening session of the second north american 
conference on preparing for climate change 
but despite the improvement there is no reason to believe the 
manmade chemicals are not destroying ozone in the atmosphere he 
said damage to that layer could increase again next year or the 
year after said watson 
ozone high in the atmosphere blocks some of the suns ultraviolet 
radiation and scientists fear that a reduction in that protective 
screen could lead to more skin cancer eye damage and other problems 
depleted ozone levels over antarctica have been widely referred 
to as a hole in the earths ozone layer and some concern has 
also been expressed over whether the problem has spread to the 
arctic 
changes in clouds temperature winds and other weather factors 
could account for the improvement this year but that doesnt mean 
there will be a permanent improvement said watson who is preparing 
for a research effort to investigate ozone levels at the north pole 
ozone levels over the antarctic in september and october were 
about 22 percent below that measured in 1979 watson said by 
contrast last year the level was 50 percent of the 1979 level 
such low ozone levels will not spread around the globe watson 
said but populated areas could see a slight decline in the ozone 
overhead and that would mean health dangers 
governments are likely to further restrict release of chemicals 
that damage the ozone however thus easing the longterm damage he 
said 
the question is not whether there will be an international 
agreement to extend the limits reached previously at montreal only 
when a new agreement will be made said watson 
the ozone hole was first reported in the early 1980s by british 
researchers it occurs within a vortex of west to east winds which 
circle the south pole in the winter and spring months equivalent 
to the summer and fall months in the northern hemisphere 
watson noted that this year the area of reduced ozone while 
smaller than in the last couple of seasons has shifted somewhat 
instead of being near the south pole the area has moved toward 
south america he commented with the region of antarctica closer to 
australia having near normal ozone levels 
of particular importance may be the reduction in the amount of 
high level clouds in the polar regions watson said those clouds 
provide ice surfaces which promote the chemical reactions in which 
chlorine and bromine compounds damage or destroy molecules of ozone 
scientists report 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

