<DOCNO> AP881206-0174 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the labor department is advising employers who 
anticipate closing their plants or implementing large layoffs in 
february to start providing 60 days advance notice as of tuesday 
despite some confusion over the timetable of the new law 
although the plantclosing notice law formally the worker 
adjustment and retraining notification or warn act does not take 
effect until feb 4 there have been different interpretations on 
whether companies should begin providing 60 days notice then or 60 
days beforehand 
some also have interpreted the new law as requiring notices for 
the first 60 days after feb 4 limited to the number of days between 
that date and when the layoffs or plant closing actually occur 
under that interpretation a layoff occurring next march 6 would 
require only 30 days advance notice to the affected workers and 
local government officials 
in an interim interpretive rule the labor department said 
all three interpretations have merit 
but until the department issues final regulatons by next april or 
the issue is resolved in court it said in a federal register notice 
that employers are best advised to proceed conservatively and to 
provide notice as early as dec 6 in view of this possible 
liability 
no notice is required for layoffs or plant closings that occur 
between now and feb 4 
the law was passed by congress last july and enacted on aug 4 
without the signature of president reagan who called it a step in 
the wrong direction 
in may reagan had vetoed a trade bill largely because it 
required 60 days notices for plant closings and layoffs of more 
than 50 people at a time 
but after polls showed that more than 80 percent of the public 
favored the mandatory notices democrats and labor unions moved to 
pass the measure as a separate law holding the trade bill hostage 
in the meantime the trade bill also eventually passed congress and 
was signed by reagan 
a 15year battle to win the mandatory notices was renewed by the 
aflcio in 1986 after an average 22 million workers a year lost 
their jobs to plant closings and mass layoffs through the first half 
of the decade 
government studies showed that more than half of those workers 
received less than two weeks advance notice and that only 18 
percent of the employers gave three weeks or more notice 
the laws enactment was the labor federations first major 
legislative victory over business opposition since last getting 
minimum wage increases through congress in 1978 
since last october the labor department had been advising 
business groups they should look upon dec 6 as the day to start 
providing the notices for layoffs occurring after feb 4 so have 
major business groups which vigorously opposed the law including 
the us chamber of commerce and national association of 
manufacturers 
sue meisinger a vice president for the american society of 
personnel administration said the effective date that notices are 
required is one of several ambiguities in the law 
youre going to find out how the ambiguities work out only 
after litigation she said there are a lot of issues to be 
played out over time a lot of employers are going to find out how 
the law works only after they get slapped with a civil complaint 
because the law does not empower any agency to enforce it 
failure to comply with it can be addressed only thourgh civil suits 
filed by affected employees unions or local governments in federal 
courts 
the courts are empowered to order up to 60 days in back pay and 
benefits plus attorneys fees to affected workers and up to 30000 
to local governments who did not get the required notices 
basically the law forbids companies employing 100 or more 
fulltime workers at any one location from ordering a plant closed 
or a mass layoff involving 50 or more people until 60 days after 
they have imformed the affected employees and local government 
officials about it 
exempted from coverage are companies with fewer than 100 
fulltime workers temporary layoffs of less than six months and 
layoffs caused by natural disasters such as last summers drought 
employers also do not have to provide the 60 days advance notice 
of the layoffs were caused by unforeseeable business circumstances 
such as the unexpected cancellation of a major contract 
international oil shortages or strikes and lockouts 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

