<TEXT>
a b52 bomber crashed on a runway and 
burst into flames during a training flight early tuesday sending 
all eight crewmen to a hospital 
the strategic air command grounded its fleet of about 260 of the 
aging planes as a precaution said maj suzanne randle public 
affairs officer for sac headquarters at offutt air force base in 
omaha neb 
another sac spokesman lt col george peck said the grounding 
was lifted tuesday evening and that each b52 will have its fuel 
system inspected before being cleared to fly some as early as 
wednesday 
randle had said earlier that she anticipated the fleet would be 
back in the air in 24 hours we dont lose many b52s it has been 
a super plane she said 
the b52 broke into three parts about 115 am est during 
practice touchandgo landings at ki sawyer air force base 
said sgt naomi siegal a spokeswoman at the sac installation here 
in a touchandgo the plane immediately takes off again rather than 
slowing down 
the practice landings followed a sevenhour training flight 
officials said 
no weapons were aboard the plane which is equipped to carry 
nuclear bombs 
the crew members crawled or were helped out of the front section 
of the broken aircraft and none suffered burns senior airman tim 
sanders said 
all aircraft exercises at sawyer were canceled and runways were 
closed said a base spokeswoman tech sgt anita bailey base 
officials said the airfield would remain closed for at least a week 
the crashed jet was one of 20 b52s stationed at sawyer 
we are counting our blessings you can put parts of a plane 
back together but you cannot put people back together bailey 
said only one crew member was in serious condition one was under 
observation but was uninjured 
lt col george peck a spokesman for sac headquarters said 
weather did not appear to be a factor in the crash the national 
weather service said a nearby municipal airport reported conditions 
at 1 am as clear with a temperature of 39 degrees 
peck said it was normal for b52 crews to be on training flights 
at that hour crews have to be trained to fly at any time of the 
day or night in any weather he said 
bailey said she did not know who was at the controls at the time 
of the crash capt mark hartney 29 was the aircraft commander 
but 1st lt michael s debruzzi 26 also was qualified to fly the 
plane she said 
maj william r kroeger 52 an instructor pilot from fountain 
hills ariz was in serious condition at marquette general hospital 
with chest injuries said hospital spokeswoman ann parent three 
other crewmen were in satisfactory or stable condition at the 
hospital she said 
three crewmen including hartney and debruzzi were moved to the 
wrightpatterson air force base hospital in dayton ohio said 
airman 1sr class blakely hicks 
the eightengine b52 which was deployed in the early 1950s is 
the militarys biggest bomber with a wingspan of 185 feet and a 
maximum takeoff weight of 488000 pounds the last b52 was 
commissioned in 1962 the original cost of the aircraft was 
9955000 said capt harry edwards at sac headquarters 
six crewmen died and 10 were injured oct 11 when an air force 
tanker enroute from ki sawyer crashed at wurtsmith air force base 
near oscoda mich the air forces investigation of the crash is 
incomplete 
