soviet human rights activist andrei sakharov will 
fly to paris on thursday ending his outspoken first trip to the 
united states with a quiet visit with his stepchildren his 
relatives said 
the 67yearold physicist and nobel prize winner who arrived in 
the united states nov 4 has been spending the last few weeks with 
efrem and tatiana yankelevich the soninlaw and daughter of his 
wife yelena bonner 
on tuesday a human rights group issued a statement from sakharov 
endorsing its call for un observers to investigate ethnic unrest 
in the soviet republics of azerbaijan and armenia 
i am deeply concerned with the situation that has emerged in 
azerbaijan and armenia sakharov said in the statement issued by 
the international league for human rights in new york 
sakharov came to the united states with the soviet delegation to 
a new organization the international foundation for the survival 
and development of humanity he is a board member of the group 
which plans to sponsor research on global problems like arms 
control hunger disease and pollution 
sakharov also traveled to new york and washington where he met 
president reagan on nov 14 
during his stay sakharov underwent cardiovascular tests in 
boston but doctors determined that he did not need a heart 
pacemaker 
the yankeleviches who live in the boston suburb of newton 
emigrated from the soviet union in 1977 yankelevich said sakharov 
was flying to paris on thursday en route to moscow 
sakharov who helped develop the soviet nuclear bomb won the 
1975 nobel peace prize for his support of human rights in the soviet 
union he was banished to the industrial city of gorky from 1980 
through 1986 because of his outspoken opposition to soviet 
intervention in afghanistan 
under soviet leader mikhail gorbachev however sakharov was 
freed from internal exile and has been allowed to travel and speak 
out on a wide range of topics 
