<TEXT>
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev in his 
united nations address wednesday may announce a decision by the 
ruling politburo to make unilateral cuts in conventional forces 
stationed in eastern europe and along the chinese border according 
to a published report 
the washington post in its wednesday editions quoted 
unidentified soviet sources saying the politburo approved the troop 
cut following a shakeup in the ruling body sept 30 
announcement of major cuts in the soviet armed forces would add 
drama to gorbachevs new york visit but not come as a big surprise 
to us officials 
gorbachev who arrived in new york on tuesday was scheduled to 
address the un general assembly on wednesday at 11 am and then 
eat lunch with president reagan and presidentelect george bush 
us officials have been predicting for a year that gorbachev 
would sharply cut the soviet armed forces and many intelligence 
analysts thought the announcement would come at the summit in moscow 
last summer 
such an announcement likely would give new momentum to 
longstalled talks on reducing warsaw pact and nato conventional 
forces in central europe and to improve the atmosphere for a summit 
scheduled next spring between gorbachev and chinese leader deng 
xiaopeng china has cut its own ground forces by one million over 
the past four years leaving it with about 4 million 
the soviet armed forces according to us government estimates 
number approximately 56 million 
the post quoted soviet sources estimating the cuts at 20 percent 
such a reduction would parallel cuts ordered in the mid1950s by 
thensoviet leader nikita khrushchev over protests from the armed 
forces 
many soviet generals are thought to oppose the cuts which 
gorbachev and his allies have hinted at in a new doctrine of 
reasonable sufficiency such a doctrine would be based on 
ability to repel aggression rather than to mount a massive offensive 
the soviet chief of staff marshal sergei akhromeyev said during 
a visit to the pentagon last july that he opposed any cut in soviet 
forces without a corresponding reduction in the conventional armies 
kept in western europe by the united states and its allies in the 
north atlantic treaty organization 
defense secretary frank c carlucci and other senior american 
officials have said they would welcome such a change but have seen 
no indication of it in the deployment of soviet forces 
</TEXT>
