<TEXT>
manufacturing productivity is still on the rise but a new survey 
finds the the nations business economists growing pessimistic about 
the economys fate in 1989 
the labor department said monday that productivity in the 
manufacturing sector improved at an annual rate of 52 percent in 
the third quarter a 72 percent jump in annual output was 
accompanied by only a 18 percent jump in employment and overtime to 
accomplish it 
businesses as a whole did not fare as well productivity among 
nonfarm businesses including the service sector that now accounts 
for about half of the nations economic activity improved by just 
19 percent on 34 percent higher output and a 15 percent rise in 
hours worked 
its pretty puny said michael evans who runs an economic 
forecasting firm in washington the ability to raise our standard 
of living is hardly improving at all thats the real effect of the 
budget deficits and these leveraged buyouts of corporations 
were spending all these billions on interest payments instead 
of capital improvements research and development and 
infrastructure he said 
still the 19 percent improvement in efficiency was better than 
the 13 percent estimated earlier before the government last week 
revised the nations gross national product upward for the third 
quarter it also nearly offset a 24 percent decline in productivity 
in the second quarter 
but the survey of 200 members of the national association of 
business economists predicted higher prices and interest rates next 
year 
an overwhelming majority of the economists 88 percent predicted 
presidentelect george bush would have to deal with a recession in 
his first two years in office 40 percent forecast the country would 
be in a downturn by this time next year 
the group predicted that the overall economy as measured by the 
gross national product would grow 22 percent next year far below 
the 35 percent forecast by the administration 
the group said consumer prices which have been rising at a 46 
percent annual rate this year would climb by 5 percent in 1989 and 
interest rates would also continue upward 
