<TEXT>
satellite photos that can tell a farmer a 
sprinkler head needs fixing or a field needs spraying may seem 
pretty far out but such spaceage technology is available and is 
expected to grow 
robert w smith a consultant in lodi calif says satellite 
technology is just beginning to break loose from government 
stranglehold and become more widely available 
particularly in the agricultural industry information needs to 
be more accessible he said 
during a recent trade show of farm equipment in fresno smith 
displayed some infrared photos taken from high above the fertile 
fields of central california 
the satellite photos were colorcoded sort of like 
electionnight television maps red spots in the photos showed the 
crops on the ground were healthy smith explained in an interview 
if we see a blemish in the red photo it tells us there is some 
kind of stress he said that might be good like irrigation 
which is a stress factor another blemish may show disease 
a photo can cover an area as large as 100 miles by 110 miles so 
the spot that has a potential problem must be magnified technicians 
can get the resolution down to one acre but usually magnify down to 
a 10acre plot smith said 
satellite photos can save money by helping farmers determine more 
precisely when and where to irrigate fertilize or spray for pests 
if you own a large amount of acreage it isnt always necessary 
to spray you dont always need all those nutrients said smith 
the use of satellite photos on the farm is still quite limited 
across the country because of the cost and complexity of the tool 
those familiar with the technology say two companies provide raw 
data from satellites orbiting the earth eosat an american firm 
based in lanham md and spot a french consortium operating from 
reston va 
the data is available in photographic form or in digital form on 
computer tape 
a single photograph or batch of tape from one of the major 
satellite services will cover a huge area and cost anywhere from 
1600 to 3800 and a farmer will also need someone to interpret 
the data for him which will increase the cost 
a slightly more costefficient service is provided by a limited 
number of smaller firms such as senstar inc of fresno which can 
shoot similar type photographs using specially equipped cameras 
mounted on aircraft 
norris packer of senstar says he uses digital cameras fitted with 
infrared and thermal sensors to shoot photographs for west coast 
farmers he also helps farmers interpret the data but he said the 
cost of 115 an acre really only makes sense for big operators of 
1000 acres or more 
the smaller farmer gets out and walks his fields every day 
anyway packer reasoned 
he claims bigger farmers might benefit from satellite photography 
because it lets them solve problems before they start to cost 
money 
oregon farmer frank lamb for example uses satellite photographs 
to keep track of 10000 acres of potatoes alfalfa and other crops 
in hermiston ore he has even gone into the business of providing 
the technology to his neighbors 
recently a photograph spotted a blemish in one of lambs fields 
which turned out to be a broken spigot the photo also warned that 
nematodes had infested another sector according to smith 
smith said the farmer estimated it would have taken his employees 
up to three weeks to find those problems which could have been 
costly 
smallscale farmers can take part in this spaceage technology 
through cooperatives or such organizations as the california farm 
bureau smith said 
packer said a tomato grower might need three photos during a 
sixweek period to find out which fields are ripe enough to pick 
his company plans an experiment over california citrus groves 
this winter to focus on frost damage and figures two pictures might 
be needed for that crop in a season 
one of the needs in the next few years smith said will be more 
companies like packers to interpet the photos for farmers 
smith contended that satellite photography is simply going back 
to the basic principle of know your land 
</TEXT>
