<TEXT>
a lawyer for dalkon shield claimants said 
tuesday that the process by which the ah robins co inc 
bankruptcy plan was approved effectively disenfranchised women with 
the largest injury claims 
a threejudge panel of the 4th circuit court of appeals heard 
arguments challenging the reorganization plan which includes a 25 
billion trust fund for women injured by the robinsmanufactured 
dalkon shield birth control device a ruling is not expected for 
several months 
alan b morrison a lawyer for the public citizen litigation 
group in washington dc argued that confirmation of the plan was 
invalid because claimants were not given a range of possible 
monetary awards when they voted to approve it and because their 
votes were not weighted 
morrison criticized the unexplained and unjustified refusal 
of us district judge robert r merhige who approved the plan in 
july to break down the 25 billion figure instead he said 
claimants were simply told they would be paid in full with no 
explanation of what that meant 
the only logical reason he didnt break out the numbers is 
because they wouldnt stand up morrison told the judges 
he said the vote in which more than 95 percent of the claimants 
returning ballots voted in favor of the plan might have come out 
differently if women with larger claims had been given weighted 
votes the bankruptcy code requires that creditors votes be 
weighted according to the size of their claims morrison said 
that in effect disenfranchised those with large claims 
morrison said 
but james c roberts an attorney for robins said weighting the 
votes would have been timeconsuming and impractical merhige 
tried mightily to come up with a system of weighted voting but 
was unable to roberts said if the value of claims had to be 
estimated in advance so that votes could be weighted the job 
would never be done he said 
roberts said merhige based the 25 billion figure on expert 
testimony at an estimation hearing last year claimants had more 
information than the law required about possible award amounts he 
said 
morrison also challenged a provision of the bankruptcy plan that 
prevents claimants from filing suit against doctors robins 
officers law firms and other third parties in the case he said 
third parties are not entitled to bankruptcy protection without 
filing for bankruptcy and claimants should be allowed to sue them 
to recover full damages 
