<TEXT>
in what would be the fastest growth since the 
early 1970s the international monetary fund said it expects the 
economies of the seven biggest industrial nations to expand 425 
percent this year 
michel camdessus director general of the imf announced the 
upward revision in the output of goods and services from 40 
percent as he said the rapid growth created a golden 
opportunity for the industrialized nations to open their markets 
to each other and to developing nations 
we are now in a good growth period camdessus told reporters 
late monday in advance of a speech tuesday at freetrade talks under 
auspices of the general agreement on tariffs and trade 
the group of seven countries covered by the imf forecast are the 
united states japan britain france west germany italy and 
canada 
the imf has steadily raised its forecast for growth in the seven 
countries from 325 percent to 38 percent to 4 percent and now 
425 percent the actual growth for this year will not be known 
until sometime in 1989 
on inflation the imf is keeping its most recent forecast of an 
inflation rate of 32 percent in the seven countries this year 
camdessus said 
in spite of the healthy growth camdessus said he was concerned 
by evidence of an increase in nontariff barriers to world trade 
among a broader range of industrialized nations 
according to a new imf report the industrial countries made more 
restrictive changes in trade policy last year than liberalizing 
changes 85 to 66 
in contrast the report said developing countries made more 
liberalizing changes than restrictive ones 227 to 126 
protectionism in industrialized nations hampers the ability of 
developing nations to grow through exports and deal with their 
crushing debt burdens 
the new imf report has other ammunition for free traders quoting 
from a united nations report it said 23 percent of the imports of 
developed countries aside from fuel were subject to nontariff 
measures last year up from 19 percent in 1981 
worldwide farm supports cost consumers and taxpayers an average 
of 185 billion a year in 1984 through 1986 the report said 
quoting the organization for economic cooperation and development 
the international monetary fund was created after world war ii to 
tide over countries that faced shortterm debt crises and to promote 
world trade it is now closely involved in the affairs of many 
heavily indebted developing countries 
camdessus said he welcomed the plans of the general agreement on 
tariffs and trade to monitor more closely the adherence of all 
nations to freetrade principles that surveillance would parallel 
the surveillance that the imf already does of countries debt 
servicing and commitment to growthoriented policies 
many developing nations already irked by the imfs involvement 
in their domestic affairs are concerned that the gatt will become 
another meddling hand 
the imf report said that since free trade helps all countries 
involved in it it does not make economic sense to delay 
unilateral measures to obtain multilateral liberalization 
in his briefing to reporters camdessus said it would be 
suicidal for nations to insist that progress in other areas of 
free trade be linked to progress on their own particular issues 
unless we press forward the risk is that we shall move 
